frameDefinitions: In this frame, an Agent or Cause changes the duration of an Event.
An event or state (here termed an Eventuality) or time-Period is described in terms of the Degree to which its duration diverges from a standard.
This frame contains (transparent ) nouns that are Units of measurement for time.
This frame consists of words that indicate the change of an Item's position on a scale (the Attribute) from a starting point (Initial_value) to an end point (Final_value).
An Item changes its physical size.
frameExamples: Don't let him <t>prolong</t> the discussion to an absurd length.
After a <t>lengthy</t> discussion with the Foreign Minister, Mr. Qian Qichen, they met the Prime Minister.
The final total was 606, scored in only 10 <t><fex name='Unit'>hours</fex></t> of excellent batsmanship.
Hawke's Bay winery <t>doubled</t> in size last year.
The pile of leaves had <t>shrunk</t> by about half after the first haul.
listRoleDefinitions: The sentient entity that changes the duration of the <fen>Event</fen>.
The <fen>Event</fen>'s duration is changed.
An event that causes the change in Event duration.
The time at which the change in duration of the Event is caused.

A situation, action or event whose duration is being described.  The Eventuality occurs as the External Argument if the adjective is used predicatively, or as the modified noun if the adjective is used attributively: <fex name='Eventuality'>The lecture</fex> was <t>short</t>. We had a <t>lengthy</t> <fex name='Eventuality'>conversation</fex>.

Sometimes these adjectives describe simply a period of time, rather than an event or state.  The Period almost invariably occurs as the modified noun with an attributive adjective: We waited for only a <t>short</t> <fex name='Period'>time</fex>. Use of the drug over a <t>lengthy</t> <fex name='Period'>period</fex> can cause memory loss.
The number of <fen>Unit</fen>s of the measured entity.
The standardized quantity in terms of which other quantities are measured.
The activity or state that takes place during the period of time under discussion.
The <fen>Attribute</fen> is a scalar property that the <fen>Item</fen> possesses.
The entity that has a position on the scale.
The distance by which an <fen>Item</fen> changes its position on the scale.
The position on the scale where the <fen>Item</fen> ends up.
The initial position on the scale from which the <fen>Item</fen> moves away.
A portion of the scale, typically identified by its end points, along which the values of the <fen>Attribute</fen> fluctuate.
A description that presents the <fen>Item</fen>'s state before the change in the <fen>Attribute</fen>'s value as an independent predication.
A description that presents the <fen>Item</fen>'s state after  the change in the <fen>Attribute</fen>'s value as an independent predication.
The <fen>Time</fen> is the time-frame in which the change of position occurs.
A location where Attribute is measured
This role identifies the <fen>Item</fen> whose size changes.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the expansion occurs.
